      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility"> ¶ Evidently a Rafflesia allied to R. Arnoldi. Only the much smaller R. Cumingi ¶  was known before from the Phillippines....</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">89.03.00f</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To the Gardeners' Chronicle</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Letter not found. The text given here is from ‘A new Rafflesia’, <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Gardeners’ chronicle</seg>, 4 May 1889, p. 562. The article opens by quoting, unacknowledged, a report in the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg> (Melbourne), 5 March 1889, p. 7, concerning the discovery in Mindanao, the Phillipines, of ‘a specimen in full bloom, a five-petalled flower, nearly a yard in diameter — as large as a carriage-wheel, in fact.’ The quotation from M's letter is introduced by ' <seg style="">Baron von </seg>
                     <seg style="font-variant: small-caps; ">Mueller</seg>
                     <seg style="">, in communicatin</seg>g to us this intelligence, says'. </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The letter is dated to March as the latest date that it could have been sent to have been reported in this issue. It is likely that M sent a cutting from the <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Argus</seg>, soon after it was published; he may not have included the name of the source newspaper.<seg style=""> </seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Evidently a Rafflesia allied to R. Arnoldi. Only the much smaller R. Cumingi<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>R. cumingii?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> was known before from the Phillippines.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See also M to L. Keogh, April 1889 (in this edition as 89-04-00b).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
